    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Intent data</strong> is a collection of behavioral signals — search queries, content consumption, website visits, and product comparisons — that reveal when a prospect is actively researching a solution in your category. Providers like Bombora, 6sense, and G2 aggregate these signals from publisher networks and review sites to answer one question: who is in-market right now?</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Conversion lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2.5x higher</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Keyword Research</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Sales cycle impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">30% shorter</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Without intent data, B2B teams guess which accounts to prioritize. With it, sales and marketing can focus on the slice of the market that is actively evaluating — compressing pipeline and lifting win rates at the same time.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is intent data?</h2>
        <p>Intent data is any digital signal that indicates a buyer is moving through an evaluation journey. The term covers a wide range of signals:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Search queries on Google or Bing for category terms, competitor names, or comparison phrases</li>
          <li>Time spent reading articles about your solution category on third-party publisher sites</li>
          <li>Activity on review aggregators like G2, Capterra, or TrustRadius — reading reviews, comparing products, downloading buying guides</li>
          <li>Engagement with competitor content or ads</li>
          <li>Repeated visits to your own pricing or features pages</li>
        </ul>
        <p>These signals are aggregated, anonymized at the individual level, and scored by account. A company "surging" on intent means its employees are collectively consuming far more content about a given topic than baseline — a strong signal that a buying conversation is opening up.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Industry benchmark</div>
          <p>Companies using intent data report <strong>2.5x higher conversion rates on outbound campaigns</strong> and sales cycles shortened by 30% (Bombora / Demand Gen Report, 2024). Outbound emails sent to accounts already showing intent achieve 2-4x higher response rates than cold sends to unqualified lists.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why intent data matters for marketing and sales</h2>
        <p>The fundamental problem intent data solves is prioritization. Every B2B company has a universe of potential buyers. At any given moment, only a small fraction is actively evaluating. Intent data tells you which fraction that is.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Better lead prioritization.</strong> Sales reps stop working cold lists. They call accounts already researching your category — where conversations start at "we're evaluating options" not "what is this?"</li>
          <li><strong>Shorter sales cycles.</strong> Reaching buyers while they're actively in-market means less time building awareness from scratch. They're already warmed up.</li>
          <li><strong>Higher win rates.</strong> Intent-driven outreach arrives when the prospect is ready to engage — not three months early or three months late.</li>
          <li><strong>Reduced content waste.</strong> Content teams can build assets around the topics prospects are actually researching right now, not topics that mattered two quarters ago.</li>
          <li><strong>Smarter ABM execution.</strong> Account-based marketing programs depend on knowing which accounts to activate and when. Intent data is the trigger layer.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How intent data works</h2>
        <p>Intent data comes from three sources, each with different reach and accuracy trade-offs.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Source</th><th>What it tracks</th><th>Accuracy</th><th>Cost</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>First-party intent</strong></td>
                <td>Your own website — page views, form starts, repeat pricing visits</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Highest — you own the data</td>
                <td>Free (already in your analytics)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Second-party intent</strong></td>
                <td>Partner data — G2 buyer intent, review comparisons, event attendance lists</td>
                <td class="cell-meh">High — named account data</td>
                <td>Platform subscription (e.g. G2 Buyer Intent)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Third-party intent</strong></td>
                <td>Aggregated publisher network — Bombora's co-op, bidstream signals, content syndication tracking</td>
                <td class="cell-meh">Directional — account-level, not individual</td>
                <td>$20K-$100K/year for full platforms</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>Most mature B2B programs layer all three. First-party data identifies warm visitors. Second-party data from review sites identifies accounts actively comparing options. Third-party data reveals accounts that haven't found you yet but are researching your category across the web.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of intent signals and what they mean</h2>
        <p>Not all intent signals are created equal. The closer the signal to a purchase decision, the higher its weight.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Topic surge (Bombora).</strong> An account consumes 3x more content on a topic than their baseline over a 30-day window. Early-stage signal — the team is starting to learn.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitor comparison.</strong> Account visits G2 pages comparing your product to a named competitor. Mid-funnel signal — they're shortlisting.</li>
          <li><strong>Pricing page visit.</strong> An identified visitor hits your pricing page twice in one week. High-purchase-intent signal — they're scoping a decision.</li>
          <li><strong>Review reading.</strong> Multiple employees at one account read your G2 reviews on the same day. The buying committee is assembling.</li>
          <li><strong>Demo request abandonment.</strong> Visitor reached your demo form but didn't submit. Warm enough for a direct outreach sequence.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="examples">Intent data in action — real examples</h2>

        <h3>1. ABM campaign activation</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company uses Bombora to monitor 500 target accounts. When an account surges on the topic "content marketing automation" for two consecutive weeks, the account automatically enters an outbound sequence. Email open rates from intent-triggered campaigns: 38% vs 11% for cold sends.</p>

        <h3>2. Content strategy from intent topics</h3>
        <p>A marketing agency tracks which topics their target accounts surge on quarterly. Rising intent on "AI content generation" six months before it became mainstream gave the content team a six-month head start publishing authoritative guides. By the time competitors caught on, the agency already ranked on page one.</p>

        <h3>3. Sales call timing</h3>
        <p>SDR teams at enterprise software companies route G2 buyer intent notifications directly into their CRM. When a prospect company views the vendor's G2 profile three times in a week, the assigned SDR gets a Slack alert. Outreach at that moment — when the buyer is actively engaged — converts at 4x the rate of standard outreach.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Intent data vs search intent — what's the difference?</h2>
        <p>These terms sound similar but serve different functions.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Intent data (B2B)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Account-level behavioral signals</li>
              <li>Identifies which companies are in-market</li>
              <li>Used by sales and demand generation teams</li>
              <li>Sources: publisher networks, review sites, your site</li>
              <li>Time horizon: right now (30-day windows)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Search intent (SEO)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Keyword-level signal about what users want</li>
              <li>Identifies what content Google should rank</li>
              <li>Used by content and SEO teams</li>
              <li>Sources: Google search queries, SERP analysis</li>
              <li>Time horizon: ongoing — informs content strategy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for using intent data</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with first-party data before buying third-party platforms.</strong> Your website analytics already contain intent signals. Set up behavior flows in GA4, track repeat pricing page visitors, and build a CRM segment before spending $50K/year on a platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Combine intent with ICP fit scoring.</strong> Intent alone is not enough. A company surging on your topic but employing 12 people may not be your buyer. Layer firmographic fit (company size, industry, tech stack) on top of intent signals for highest-quality prioritization.</li>
          <li><strong>Define your surge threshold per topic.</strong> "Surging" means different things for different topics. Calibrate what a meaningful intent spike looks like for each keyword cluster — not just a default multiplier from your data provider.</li>
          <li><strong>Act within 24-48 hours of a signal.</strong> Intent signals are perishable. An account researching options today may have a vendor selected by next week. Automated workflows that trigger sales sequences within hours of a signal dramatically outperform weekly batch exports.</li>
          <li><strong>Use intent to personalize, not just prioritize.</strong> When you know a prospect has been reading about AI content generation, your outreach references that topic — not generic product messaging. Personalization from intent context lifts reply rates significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit your intent provider's co-op network quarterly.</strong> Third-party intent quality depends on which publishers contribute to the provider's network. Bombora's network and a smaller competitor's network cover different corners of the web. Ask your provider which sites contribute most to signals in your category.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — treating intent data as a lead list</div>
          <p>Intent data tells you which accounts are researching — not which individuals are ready to buy. Using an account-level intent surge to spam every contact at a company is the fastest way to burn a relationship before it starts. Use intent to time and personalize outreach, not to carpet-bomb a buying committee.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common intent data mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring first-party signals.</strong> Teams buy expensive third-party platforms while leaving their own GA4 and CRM behavior data unmapped. Start with what you own.</li>
          <li><strong>No ICP filter on intent signals.</strong> Without an ideal customer profile filter, your sales team wastes time on in-market companies that will never buy from you.</li>
          <li><strong>Acting too slowly.</strong> Intent signals are time-sensitive. Batch processing weekly means you contact prospects days after their interest peaks.</li>
          <li><strong>Single signal reliance.</strong> One intent touch is not a buying signal — it's noise. Wait for pattern confirmation across multiple signals before activating.</li>
          <li><strong>No content alignment.</strong> Knowing a prospect surges on "content automation" but sending them generic product emails defeats the purpose. Intent data only pays off when messaging matches the signal.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is intent data the same as search data?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Search data shows what people type into Google. Intent data is broader — it includes search behavior plus content consumption on third-party sites, review site activity, ad engagement, and publisher network signals aggregated by providers like Bombora.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How accurate is third-party intent data?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Third-party intent data is directional, not exact. It signals which accounts are surging on a topic, not which specific individuals are buying. Accuracy improves significantly when you layer third-party signals on top of first-party data from your own site.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does intent data work for small businesses?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Full intent data platforms ($20K-$100K/year) are priced for mid-market and enterprise. Small teams can start with free first-party signals: GA4 behavior flows, email open and click patterns, and content download tracking give meaningful signal without platform costs.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is a buyer intent signal?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A buyer intent signal is any digital behavior suggesting a prospect is evaluating solutions. Examples: reading comparison articles, visiting competitor review pages on G2 or Capterra, downloading pricing guides, or repeatedly visiting your pricing page within a short window.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do companies use intent data in practice?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>The most common use cases are ABM campaign activation (triggering outreach when a target account surges on relevant topics), sales prioritization (SDRs call intent-signaling accounts first), and content personalization (serving relevant case studies to in-market visitors).</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

